 gradation as a subcompositional phenomenon. These topics are investigated from a cross-linguistic perspective. The languages of investigation include, among others, German, Russian and French.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 4aGradation. 4asemantic analysis. 4asyntactic analysis. 4averb gradation. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  aAktionsart.  aChange of state verbs.  aCollaborative Research Center.  aCompositional patterns.  aCross-categorical distribution.  aCross-linguistic distribution.  aDFG.  aDeutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft.  aDissertations in Language and Cognition.  aDoetjes.  aEmission verbs.  aErratic verbs.  aEvent-dependent degree gradation.  aExperiencer verbs.  aFrench.  aGerhard Schurz.  aGerman.  aGrammatical aspect.  aHana Filip.  aHeinrich-Heine-Universität Düsseldorf.  aJapanese degree verb.  aKennedy.  aLaura Kallmeyer.  aManner/result complementarity.  aMcNally.  aObject-experiencer verbs.  aPeter Indefrey.  aPredicate decomposition.  aReference Grammar.  aRobert D. Van Valin, Jr.  aRole Grammar.  aRussian.  aSFB 991.  aScalar changes.  aScope relationships.  aSebastian Löbner.  aSemantic type.  aSemantic verb classes.  aSemantics of intensifiers.  aSonderforschungsbereich 991.  aSubcompositionality of verbal degree gradation.  aSubject-experiencer verbs.  aTenny.  aThe structure of representations in language, cognition and science.  aTsujimura.  aVecchiato.  aadjective gradation.  aadnominal degree expression.  aadverbial beaucoup.  acase study.  aclassification.  acognitive concepts.  